g Britain’s imperial ambitions, between 1750 and 1930. New and established researchers from Canada, Scotland and the United States engage with the core themes of migration, dispossession, religion, identity, and commemoration in a way that diverges markedly from existing scholarship. The research shines much-needed light on groups traditionally excluded from Britain’s broader imperial narrative, highlighting the indigenous experience and the presence and agency of slaves, free people of colour and religious minorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aChopra, Ruma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardwick, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKehoe, S. Karly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeough, Willeen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorneski, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontgomery, Alexandra L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, John G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRitchie, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTindley, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVance, Michael E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVance, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311078041340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147445905140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474459051423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474459051/ori